content.description: Starts matched on a long slopey lip in between the other two climbs and moves out right beneath the big spike horn before coming out from down under and going over.Thanks to M Cat for coming up with this one!

Sit start laying matched on a very low, flat hold and move out from under the bottom of the rocky strip through the folds and top out. Lowball, starts like coming out of a roof with a cool intermediate crack to work with while coming out from under.The landing and the climb stay just above the tide line so at high tide you start laying in a dry space under the rock with the water lapping around you.
content.location: This problem is on the first and lowest strip of rock approaching the rocky neck from the east side. It's close to where the strip ends in the water and it faces east.

content.description: Sit start underneath the large spike on good holds, pull onto to the underside of it and topout.
content.location: To the right of "Under The Sea", underneath the large spike feature that forms the south side of the split between the strip of rock. Faces east.

content.description: A rocky peninsula that stays above the tide with interesting geological features, a couple steep walls and a few lowball problems.
